In 2013, Orthodox Christians constituted 58% of Crimea's population, followed by Muslims (15%) and those who believe in God without adhering to a specific religion (10%).

Following the [2014 Russian annexation of Crimea](/2014_Russian_annexation_of_Crimea), 38 out of 46 [Ukrainian Orthodox Church – Kyiv Patriarchate](/Ukrainian_Orthodox_Church_%E2%80%93_Kyiv_Patriarchate) parishes ceased to exist, with some churches seized by Russian authorities. The [Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate)](/Ukrainian_Orthodox_Church_(Moscow_Patriarchate)) maintained control of its eparchies in Crimea.

### Culture

*See also: [Crimean legends](/Crimean_legends) and [Crimean Tatar cuisine](/Crimean_Tatar_cuisine)*

[Alexander Pushkin](/Alexander_Pushkin) in Bakhchysarai Palace. Painting by [Grigory Chernetsov](/Grigory_Chernetsov).

The earliest known literary work in the [Crimean Tatar language](/Crimean_Tatar_language), a version of [Yusuf and Zulaykha](/Yusuf_and_Zulaykha), is attributed to [Mahmud Qırımlı](/Mahmud_Q%C4%B1r%C4%B1ml%C4%B1) around the early 13th century. [Alexander Pushkin](/Alexander_Pushkin) visited [Bakhchysarai](/Bakhchysarai) in 1820, later writing the poem [The Fountain of Bakhchisaray](/The_Fountain_of_Bakhchisaray). Polish poet [Adam Mickiewicz](/Adam_Mickiewicz)'s seminal work, [The Crimean Sonnets](/The_Crimean_Sonnets), was inspired by his 1825 journey. These sonnets offer a romanticized, yet melancholic, portrayal of the region and the exile's longing for home.

[Ivan Aivazovsky](/Ivan_Aivazovsky), a renowned 19th-century marine painter of Armenian descent, was born and lived most of his life in [Feodosia](/Feodosia). His paintings often depicted the Black Sea, and he also created works related to the Crimean War.

Crimean Tatar singer [Jamala](/Jamala) won the [Eurovision Song Contest 2016](/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2016) representing Ukraine with her song "[1944](/1944_(song))", which commemorated the historical deportation of Crimean Tatars.

### Sport

Following the [2014 annexation](/Annexation_of_Crimea_by_the_Russian_Federation), top football clubs withdrew from the [Ukrainian leagues](/Ukrainian_football_league_system). While some registered for Russian leagues, the [Football Federation of Ukraine](/Football_Federation_of_Ukraine) objected. [UEFA](/UEFA) ruled that Crimean clubs should form their own league system, leading to the establishment of the [Crimean Premier League](/Crimean_Premier_League).

Several Crimean-born athletes have been permitted to compete for Russia, including European javelin champion [Vera Rebrik]. Due to current [suspensions of Russian athletes](/Doping_in_Russia), Rebrik competes as a "neutral" athlete.

